ted within a 65 mile radius: [[Mount Graham]] (31 miles north), [[Chiricahua Peak]] (42 miles southeast), [[Mount Lemmon]] (57 miles west), and [[Miller Peak (Arizona)|Miller Peak]] (65 miles southwest). Scores of birds including [[Sandhill Cranes]] winter in the area, with some migrating from as far away as [[Siberia]]. A very large dry lakebed, the [[Willcox Playa]], is located 5 miles south of the city. It is the remnant of the [[Pleistocene|Ice Age]]-era Lake Cochise.\n\nWillcox's high desert climate gives it large [[diurnal temperature variation]], making it ideal for [[wine]] cultivation.\n\n==History==\nOriginally known as \"Maley\", the town was founded in 1880 as a [[whistlestop]] on the [[Southern Pacific Railroad]] because of its position approximately halfway between El Paso, Texas and Phoenix, Arizona. It was renamed in honor of a visit by General [[Orlando B. Willcox]] in 1889. In the early 20th century, Willcox was a national leader in [[cattle]] production. Agriculture remains important to the local economy, but [[Interstate 10]] has replaced the railroad as the major transportation link, and much of the economy is now tied to the highway, which runs immediately north of the town.\n\nWillcox is the birthplace of [[Rex Allen]], known as \"The Arizona Cowboy\", who wrote and recorded many songs, starred in several [[Western (genre)|Westerns]] during the early 1950s and in the [[broadcast syndication|syndicated]] [[television series]] ''[[Frontier Doctor]]'' (1958\u20131959). Parts of the 1993 American neo-noir film  ''[[Red Rock West]]'' starring [[Nicolas Cage]], [[Lara Flynn Boyle]], [[J. T. Walsh]] and [[Dennis Hopper]] were filmed in Willcox.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} A short film documentary called \"Lonesome Willcox\" released in 2018 documented the town's country music radio station [[KHIL]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nWillcox became Arizona's second federally designated wine growing region in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/travel/arizona/2016/09/13/willcox-wins-federal-designation-unique-arizona-wine-region/90094172/|title=Feds call Willcox unique Arizona wine region|first=Richard|last=Ruelas|website=azcentral}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nWillcox is located in northern Cochise County, in the [[Sulphur Springs Valley]].<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Interstate 10 serves the city with three exits and leads {{convert|35|mi}} southwest to [[Benson, Arizona]], and {{convert|74|mi}} east to [[Lordsburg, New Mexico]]. According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|16.3|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|15.9|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|0.3|km2|order=flip}}, or 2.13%, is water.\n\n==Climate==\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Willcox, Arizona\n|single line = Y\n|Jan high F = 61\n|Feb high F = 65\n|Mar high F = 71\n|Apr high F = 79\n|May high F = 88\n|Jun high F = 96\n|Jul high F = 96\n|Aug high F = 93\n|Sep high F = 90\n|Oct high F = 80\n|Nov high F = 70\n|Dec high F = 60\n|Jan record high F = 81\n|Feb record high F = 88\n|Mar record high F = 92\n|Apr record high F = 97\n|May record high F = 105\n|Jun record high F = 110\n|Jul record high F = 110\n|Aug record high F = 106\n|Sep record high F = 105\n|Oct record high F = 101\n|Nov record high F = 91\n| Dec record high F = 81\n|year record high F = 110\n|year high F = 79\n|Jan low F = 28\n|Feb low F = 31\n|Mar low F = 35\n|Apr low F = 40\n|May low F = 49\n|Jun low F = 57\n|Jul low F = 65\n|Aug low F = 64\n|Sep low F = 57\n|Oct low F = 44\n|Nov low F = 33\n|Dec low F = 27\n|Jan record low F = \u22121\n|Feb record low F = 2\n|Mar record low F = 6\n|Apr record low F = 9\n|May record low F = 11\n|Jun record low F = 27\n|Jul record low F = 42\n|Aug record low F = 41\n|Sep record low F = 30\n|Oct record low F = 15\n|Nov record low F = 8\n|Dec record low F = \u22127\n|year record low F = \u22127\n|year low F = 44\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 1.09\n|Feb precipitation inch =  0.96\n|Mar precipitation inch =  0.68\n|Apr precipitation inch =  0.33\n|May precipitation inch =  0.39\n|Jun precipitation inch =  0.46\n|Jul precipitation inch =  2.61\n|Aug precipitation inch =  2.53\n|Sep precipitation inch =  1.18\n|Oct precipitation inch =  1.16\n|Nov precipitation inch =  0.71\n|Dec precipitation inch =  1.25\n|year precipitation inch =\n|Jan snow inch = 0.9\n|Feb snow inch = 0.9\n|Mar snow inch = 0.7\n|Apr snow inch = 0.2\n|May snow inch = 0\n|Jun snow inch = 0\n|Jul snow inch = 0\n|Aug snow inch = 0\n|Sep snow inch = 0\n|Oct snow inch = 0\n|Nov snow inch = 0.1\n|Dec snow inch = 1.5\n|year snow inch= 4.3\n|source 1 = <ref>[http://wwworigin.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/USAZ0263]</ref>}}\n\nWillcox's high elevation gives it a milder climate than the nearby [[Arizona Sun Valley]] and [[Sonoran Desert]]. It also receives more rainfall than [[Tucson]] and [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] due to the summer [[monsoon]] rains.\n\n==Economy==\nMajor employers in Willcox include [[Willcox Unified School District]], [[TravelCenters of America]], Northern Cochise Community Hospital, Valley [[Utility cooperative#Telephone cooperatives|Telephone Cooperative]], the [[United States Border Patrol|Border Patrol]], and [[Safeway Inc.|Safeway]]. [[NatureSweet]] has a greenhouse outside town.<ref>Search Results - Willcox, Arizona- [http://www.referenceusa.com/ ReferenceUSA] Current Businesses</ref>\n\n==Wine country==\nThe Willcox wine region produces 74 percent of the wine grapes grown in the state of Arizona.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wines of Wilcox|url=http://www.willcoxwines.com/|website=Wines of Wilcox|publisher=Wines of Wilcox|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> Willcox is the largest-grape growing region in Arizona and grows more wine grapes than any other region in the state<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://willcoxwines.com/about.html|title=About Wines of Willcox - Events and Adventures in Arizona Wine Country|last=|first=|date=|website=willcoxwines.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> and offers a wide variety of wines to choose from. Grape varietals grown include [[Petite Sirah]], [[Malvasia Bianca]], [[Sangiovese]], [[Chenin blanc]], [[Syrah]], [[Colombard]], [[Sauvignon blanc]], [[Corvina]], [[Merlot]], [[Malbec]], [[Tannat]], [[Cabernet Franc]], [[Chardonnay]], [[Tempranillo]], [[Cabernet Sauvignon]] and [[Mourv\u00e8dre]].\n\n==Arts and culture==\nRex Allen Days is a multi-day event that takes place the first weekend in October. It started in 1951 to honor [[Rex Allen]]. The event includes the annual parade, rodeos, fairs, car show and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rexallendays.org/|title=Rodeo {{!}} Willcox {{!}} Rex Allen Days|last=|first=|date=|website=radsite|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\nWillcox Wine Country hosts two festivals, one in May and one in October. The event grows in size every year and includes live music and multiple arts and crafts vendors. Willcox Wine Festivals is listed as one of the top 10 wine festivals in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tucsonfoodie.com/2019/10/08/willcox-wine-country-fall-festival-2019/|title=15 Arizona wineries pour into Willcox Wine Country Fall Festival|last=|first=|date=2019-10-08|website=Tucson Foodie|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1890= 396\n|1910= 1632\n|1920= 905\n|1930= 806\n|1940= 884\n|1950= 1266\n|1960= 2441\n|1970= 2568\n|1980= 3243\n|1990= 3122\n|2000= 3733\n|2010= 3757\n|estyear=2019\n|estimate=3445\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the census of 2000, there were 3,733 people, 1,383 households, and 947 families residing in the city.  The population density was 622.3 people per square mile (240.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 74.95% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 0.70% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 1.61% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.83% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.05% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 17.63% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 4.23% from two or more races.  41.71% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race. The median income for a household in the city was $24,334. 21.6% of families and 27.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 36.6% of those under age 18 and 24.6% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n\nSeventeen miles north of Willcox on what was once the York ranch, there are now miles of apple orchards and pistachio groves.\n\n==Media==\n[[KHIL]] \"Classic Country\" 1250 AM and 98.1 FM has served the region since 1958.\n\n==Further reading==\nVernon B. Schultz, \"Southwestern Town: The Story of Willcox, Arizona,\" The University of Arizona Press, 1964\n\nKathy Klump and Peta-Anne Tenney, \"Willcox,\" Arcadia Publishing Library Editions, 2009\n\n== People ==\n* [[Rex Allen]] (1920\u20131999), film and television actor, singer and songwriter\n* [[Lilly McElroy]] (born 1980), photographer\n* [[Chalky Wright]] (1912\u20131957), boxing champion in [[International Boxing Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Tanya Tucker]] (born 1958), American country music artist, spent early childhood in Willcox, AZ\n* [[Ted DiBiase]] (born 1954), American former professional wrestler, manager, ordained minister and color commentator, moved to Willcox, Arizona to live with his grandparents\n*Vince Moreno, American country music artist and musician and stand-up comedian<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vincemoreno.net/|title=VINCE MORENO Music|last=|first=|date=|website=www.vincemoreno.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Rex Allen Arizona Cowboy Museum and Willcox Cowboy Hall of Fame]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Willcox}}\n* [http://www.cityofwillcox.org City of Willcox official website]\n* [http://www.willcoxrangenews.com ''Arizona Range News''] - newspaper\n* [http://www.smalltownpapers.com/listAZR.htm Arizona Range News Archives]\n* [https://www.pinterest.com/arizonagtcoop/willcox-arizona Willcox, AZ Pinterest]\n{{Cochise County, Arizona}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Cochise County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Cities in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1880]]\n[[Category:1880 establishments in Arizona Territory]]\n[[Category:Willcox, Arizona| ]]\n", "name_user": "Lam-ang", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed GNIS ID, remove file prefix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willcox,_Arizona"}
{"title_page": "Dirty Hit", "text_new": "{{short description|British record label}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2010}}\n{{Infobox record label\n| image = \n| founded     = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1 December 2009}}\n| founder     = Jamie Oborne, Brian Smith, Ugo Ehiogu\n| status = <!--Leave blank unless \"Inactive\" or \"Defunct\"-->\n| distributor = {{flatlist|\n* [[Ingrooves]] (digital)\n* [[Polydor]] (only [[The 1975]]) \n* [[Universal Music Group]] (rest of the world)\n* [[Sony Music Group]] (Australia and New Zealand) \n* [[Interscope Records]] (North America) \n}}\n| genre = Various, with a focus on [[Alternative rock|alternative]]\n| country = [[United Kingdom]] \n| location =\n| url = {{URL|www.dirtyhit.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Dirty Hit''' is a British [[independent record label]] founded in December 2009 by Jamie Oborne,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/theyre-at-the-peak-of-their-powers-dirty-hits-jamie-oborne-tells-us-about-the-future-of-the-1975-and-whats-next-for-the-label-2447036|title=\"They're at the peak of their powers\" \u2013 Dirty Hit's Jamie Oborne tells us about the future of The 1975 and what's next for the label|last=Andrew Trendell|date=2019-02-13|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>, Brian Smith and former [[England national football team|England]] footballer, [[Ugo Ehiogu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/pg53zm/rip-ugo-ehiogu-dirty-hit-records-musical-legacy|title=RIP Ugo Ehiogu, Who Brought Genuine Passion to a Cynical Music Business|last=Harrison|first=Angus|date=2017-04-21|website=Noisey|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> It is currently based in West London, England.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dirtyhit.co.uk/ |title=Dirty Hit! |accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Their releases are distributed by Ingrooves Music Group. \n\nSince Dirty Hit's inception, Oborne has been the main driving force behind the label. Previously part of a signed band, he moved into artist management aiming to provide artist support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coupdemainmagazine.com/dirty-hit/13187|title=Interview: Dirty Hit\u2019s Jamie Oborne on the \"business of selling identity\".|last=Graves|first=Shahlin|date=2017-09-02|website=Coup De Main Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> Providing a platform for two acts that Oborne managed, was the main motivation behind starting the label. Both the 1975 and Benjamin Francis Leftwich thus became the first signings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/managers-should-make-decisions-on-reason-logic-and-knowing-their-artists/|title='Managers should make decisions based on reason, logic \u2013 and knowing their artists'|date=2016-02-29|website=Music Business Worldwide|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> [[The 1975]] were the first act on the label to achieve mainstream success, having achieved a number 1 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] in September 2013 with their [[Eponym|eponymous]] [[The 1975 (album)|debut album]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-1975-score-debut-number-1-album-2474/ |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |title= The 1975 score debut number 1 album |accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> Oborne also manages some of the groups on the label through his All On Red management company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/the-coolest-of-the-cool-matthew-healy-and-jamie-oborne-talk-ambitions-as-the-1975-drop-album-number-three/074620|title='The coolest of the cool': Matthew Healy and Jamie Oborne talk ambitions as The 1975 drop album number three|website=www.musicweek.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> In February 2019 it was announced that The 1975 had signed a new three-album deal with the record company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/106689-the-1975-sign-new-deal-with-dirty-hit-record-label/|title=The 1975 sign new deal with Dirty Hit record label|date=2019-02-12|website=The List|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, the label organised the Dirty Hit Tour featuring Superfood, King Nun and Pale Waves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2017/05/15/dirty-hit-tour-2017-pale-waves-king-nun-superfood|title=It's a Dirty Hit!|last=Wright|first=Lisa|date=15 May 2017|website=DIY|access-date=2017-05-20}}</ref>\n\n== Artists ==\n* [[Benjamin Francis Leftwich]]\n* [[Wolf Alice]]\n* [[The 1975]]\n* [[No Rome]]\n* [[The Japanese House]]\n* Ben Khan\n* [[QTY (band)|QTY]]\n* [[Pale Waves]]\n* [[King Nun]]\n* 404\n* Superfood\n* [[Marika Hackman]]\n* Caleb Steph\n* Just Banco\n* The Candescents\n* [[Beabadoobee]]\n* AMA\n* Oscar Lang\n* Gia Ford\n* [[Rina Sawayama]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.dirtyhit.co.uk}}\n* [http://www.littlecomets.com/ Little Comets Official Website]\n* [http://www.generalfiasco.co.uk General Fiasco Official Website]\n* [http://www.fossilcollective.com/ Fossil Collective Official Website]\n* [http://www.benjaminfrancisleftwich.com/ Benjamin Francis Leftwich Official Website]\n* [http://www.the1975.com/ The 1975 Official Website]\n\n[[Category:British record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2009]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{UK-record-label-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British record label}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2010}}\n{{Infobox record label\n| image = \n| founded     = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1 December 2009}}\n| founder     = Jamie Oborne, Brian Smith, Ugo Ehiogu\n| status = <!--Leave blank unless \"Inactive\" or \"Defunct\"-->\n| distributor = {{flatlist|\n* [[Ingrooves]] (digital)\n* [[Polydor]] (only [[The 1975]]) \n* [[Universal Music Group]] (rest of the world)\n* [[Sony Music Group]] (Australia and New Zealand) \n* [[Interscope Records]] (North America) \n}}\n| genre = Various, with a focus on [[Alternative rock|alternative]]\n| country = [[United Kingdom]] \n| location =\n| url = {{URL|www.dirtyhit.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Dirty Hit''' is a British [[independent record label]] founded in December 2009 by Jamie Oborne,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/theyre-at-the-peak-of-their-powers-dirty-hits-jamie-oborne-tells-us-about-the-future-of-the-1975-and-whats-next-for-the-label-2447036|title=\"They're at the peak of their powers\" \u2013 Dirty Hit's Jamie Oborne tells us about the future of The 1975 and what's next for the label|last=Andrew Trendell|date=2019-02-13|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>, Brian Smith and former [[England national football team|England]] footballer, [[Ugo Ehiogu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/pg53zm/rip-ugo-ehiogu-dirty-hit-records-musical-legacy|title=RIP Ugo Ehiogu, Who Brought Genuine Passion to a Cynical Music Business|last=Harrison|first=Angus|date=2017-04-21|website=Noisey|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> It is currently based in West London, England.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dirtyhit.co.uk/ |title=Dirty Hit! |accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Their releases are distributed by Ingrooves Music Group. \n\nSince Dirty Hit's inception, Oborne has been the main driving force behind the label. Previously part of a signed band, he moved into artist management aiming to provide artist support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coupdemainmagazine.com/dirty-hit/13187|title=Interview: Dirty Hit\u2019s Jamie Oborne on the \"business of selling identity\".|last=Graves|first=Shahlin|date=2017-09-02|website=Coup De Main Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> Providing a platform for two acts that Oborne managed, was the main motivation behind starting the label. Both the 1975 and Benjamin Francis Leftwich thus became the first signings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/managers-should-make-decisions-on-reason-logic-and-knowing-their-artists/|title='Managers should make decisions based on reason, logic \u2013 and knowing their artists'|date=2016-02-29|website=Music Business Worldwide|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> [[The 1975]] were the first act on the label to achieve mainstream success, having achieved a number 1 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] in September 2013 with their [[Eponym|eponymous]] [[The 1975 (album)|debut album]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-1975-score-debut-number-1-album-2474/ |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |title= The 1975 score debut number 1 album |accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> Oborne also manages some of the groups on the label through his All On Red management company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/the-coolest-of-the-cool-matthew-healy-and-jamie-oborne-talk-ambitions-as-the-1975-drop-album-number-three/074620|title='The coolest of the cool': Matthew Healy and Jamie Oborne talk ambitions as The 1975 drop album number three|website=www.musicweek.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> In February 2019 it was announced that The 1975 had signed a new three album deal with the record company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/106689-the-1975-sign-new-deal-with-dirty-hit-record-label/|title=The 1975 sign new deal with Dirty Hit record label|date=2019-02-12|website=The List|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, the label organised the Dirty Hit Tour featuring Superfood, King Nun and Pale Waves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2017/05/15/dirty-hit-tour-2017-pale-waves-king-nun-superfood|title=It's a Dirty Hit!|last=Wright|first=Lisa|date=15 May 2017|website=DIY|access-date=2017-05-20}}</ref>\n\n== Artists ==\n* [[Benjamin Francis Leftwich]]\n* [[Wolf Alice]]\n* [[The 1975]]\n* [[No Rome]]\n* [[The Japanese House]]\n* Ben Khan\n* [[QTY (band)|QTY]]\n* [[Pale Waves]]\n* [[King Nun]]\n* 404\n* Superfood\n* [[Marika Hackman]]\n* 