 clips]]\n[[Category:National symbols of the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Dave.Dunford", "label": "safe", "comment": "tweak ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northern_lapwing"}
{"title_page": "Avie Records", "text_new": "{{Infobox record label\n| name        = Avie Records\n| image       =\n| parent      = \n| founded     = 2002\n| founder     = Simon Foster <br />Melanne Mueller\n| status      = \n| distributor = \n| genre       = [[Classical music]]\n| country     =\n| location    = \n| url         = http://www.avie-records.com/\n}}\nAVIE Records is a UK-based independent classical music recording company founded in 2002 by Simon Foster and Melanne Mueller who devised a unique business model based on artist ownership. Foster and Mueller continue to run the company together with executives Barry McCann and Steve Winn. The label maintains offices in the UK and US. \n\nAVIE's catalogue includes over 300 recordings by artists including [[Harry Bicket]] and the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]], [[Semyon Bychkov (conductor)|Semyon Bychkov]] and the [[WDR Symphony Orchestra Cologne|WDR Symphony Orchestra]], [[Augustin Hadelich]], [[Andreas Haefliger]], the [[Handel and Haydn Society]], [[Jon Lord]], [[Ant\u00f4nio Meneses]], [[New York Polyphony]], [[Menahem Pressler]], [[Rachel Barton Pine]], and [[Jeannette Sorrell]] and [[Apollo's Fire]]. \n\nAVIE works with various independent distributors worldwide making CDs available in over 30 countries. Recordings are widely available on digital platforms including Apple Music, Amazon and Spotify, among many others.\n\nAVIE's artists have won numerous international awards. In 2016, [[Laura Karpman]] won a [[Grammy Award]] for her creation ''ASK YOUR MAMA'' based on the poetry of [[Langston Hughes]]. [[Lorraine Hunt Lieberson]], [[Monica Huggett]], the [[Dufay Collective]] and Ant\u00f4nio Meneses have received Grammy Nominations. Gramophone Awards have gone to [[Julian Bream]] for his DVD ''My Life in Music'', Adrian Chandler and his ensemble [[La Serenissima (musical ensemble)|La Serenissima]], for ''Vivaldi: The French Connection'', [[Andrew Parrott]] and the [[Taverner Consort and Players|Taverner Consort]] for ''Western Wind: Mass by John Taverner and Court Music for Henry VIII'', [[Trevor Pinnock]] for his [[Brandenburg Concertos]] with the specially formed European Brandenburg Ensemble, and viol quartet [[Phantasm (music group)|Phantasm]] for its recording of [[Orlando Gibbons|Gibbons]]\u2019 Consorts. Other international citations include France's [[Diapason d\u2019or de l\u2019ann\u00e9e]] for [[Simon Trp\u010deski]]\u2019s [[Rachmaninov]] ''Piano Concertos Nos. 2 and 3'', with [[Vasily Petrenko]] and the [[Royal Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra]].\n\nProjects released by AVIE include the first release by the [[Seattle Opera]] of Wagner's [[Ring cycle]]; numerous world premiere recordings of the music of [[Hans G\u00e1l]] including the Four Symphonies by [[Kenneth Woods]] and [[Orchestra of the Swan]], the Cello Concerto by Ant\u00f4nio Meneses with Claudio Cruz and the [[Royal Northern Sinfonia]], the Piano Concerto by [[Sarah Beth Briggs]] with Kenneth Woods and the Royal Northern Sinfonia, and the complete works for solo piano by [[Leon McCawley]]; the world premiere recording of [[Samuel Coleridge-Taylor]]\u2019s Violin Concerto by [[Philippe Graffin]] with Michael Hankinson and the [[Johannesburg Philharmonic Orchestra]]; and the complete [[Beethoven symphonies]] by [[Douglas Boyd]] and the [[Manchester Camerata]].\n\nAVIE passionately nurtures young, emerging talent and has helped to build the international reputations of several artists. These include Avery Fisher Career Grant, Warner Music Prize and Grammy Award winner violinist Augustin Hadelich; Luiza Borac who won a BBC Music Magazine Award for her survey of Enescu's Piano Works; and Vivaldi authority Adrian Chandler who was the 2010 Gramophone Award winner in the Baroque Instrumental category. \n\nSince its inception, AVIE has had a relationship with the [[San Francisco Symphony]], coordinating international distribution and marketing of the orchestra's in-house label SFS Media which has won numerous Grammy Awards for its [[Symphonies of Mahler|Mahler Symphony cycle]] with conductor [[Michael Tilson Thomas]]. \n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.avie-records.com/}}\n\n{{UK-record-label-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Classical music record labels|Avie Records]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox record label\n| name        = Avie Records\n| image       =\n| parent      = \n| founded     = 2002\n| founder     = Simon Foster <br />Melanne Mueller\n| status      = \n| distributor = \n| genre       = [[Classical music]]\n| country     =\n| location    = \n| url         = http://www.avie-records.com/\n}}\nAVIE Records is a UK-based independent classical music recording company founded in 2002 by Simon Foster and Melanne Mueller who devised a unique business model based on artist ownership. Foster and Mueller continue to run the company together with executives Barry McCann and Steve Winn. The label maintains offices in the UK and US. \n\nAVIE\u2019s catalogue includes over 300 recordings by artists including [[Harry Bicket]] and the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]], [[Semyon Bychkov (conductor)|Semyon Bychkov]] and the [[WDR Symphony Orchestra Cologne|WDR Symphony Orchestra]], [[Augustin Hadelich]], [[Andreas Haefliger]], the [[Handel and Haydn Society]], [[Jon Lord]], [[Ant\u00f4nio Meneses]], [[New York Polyphony]], [[Menahem Pressler]], [[Rachel Barton Pine]], and [[Jeannette Sorrell]] and [[Apollo's Fire]]. \n\nAVIE works with various independent distributors worldwide making CDs available in over 30 countries. Recordings are widely available on digital platforms including Apple Music, Amazon and Spotify, among many others.\n\nAVIE\u2019s artists have won numerous international awards. In 2016, [[Laura Karpman]] won a [[Grammy Award]] for her creation ''ASK YOUR MAMA'' based on the poetry of [[Langston Hughes]]. [[Lorraine Hunt Lieberson]], [[Monica Huggett]], the [[Dufay Collective]] and Ant\u00f4nio Meneses have received Grammy Nominations. Gramophone Awards have gone to [[Julian Bream]] for his DVD ''My Life in Music'', Adrian Chandler and his ensemble [[La Serenissima (musical ensemble)|La Serenissima]], for ''Vivaldi: The French Connection'', [[Andrew Parrott]] and the [[Taverner Consort and Players|Taverner Consort]] for ''Western Wind: Mass by John Taverner and Court Music for Henry VIII'', [[Trevor Pinnock]] for his [[Brandenburg Concertos]] with the specially formed European Brandenburg Ensemble, and viol quartet [[Phantasm (music group)|Phantasm]] for its recording of [[Orlando Gibbons|Gibbons]]\u2019 Consorts. Other international citations include France\u2019s [[Diapason d\u2019or de l\u2019ann\u00e9e]] for [[Simon Trp\u010deski]]\u2019s [[Rachmaninov]] ''Piano Concertos Nos. 2 and 3'', with [[Vasily Petrenko]] and the [[Royal Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra]].\n\nProjects released by AVIE include the first release by the [[Seattle Opera]] of Wagner\u2019s [[Ring cycle]]; numerous world premiere recordings of the music of [[Hans G\u00e1l]] including the Four Symphonies by [[Kenneth Woods]] and [[Orchestra of the Swan]], the Cello Concerto by Ant\u00f4nio Meneses with Claudio Cruz and the [[Royal Northern Sinfonia]], the Piano Concerto by [[Sarah Beth Briggs]] with Kenneth Woods and the Royal Northern Sinfonia, and the complete works for solo piano by [[Leon McCawley]]; the world premiere recording of [[Samuel Coleridge-Taylor]]\u2019s Violin Concerto by [[Philippe Graffin]] with Michael Hankinson and the [[Johannesburg Philharmonic Orchestra]]; and the complete [[Beethoven symphonies]] by [[Douglas Boyd]] and the [[Manchester Camerata]].\n\nAVIE passionately nurtures young, emerging talent and has helped to build the international reputations of several artists. These include Avery Fisher Career Grant, Warner Music Prize and Grammy Award winner violinist Augustin Hadelich; Luiza Borac who won a BBC Music Magazine Award for her survey of Enescu\u2019s Piano Works; and Vivaldi authority Adrian Chandler who was the 2010 Gramophone Award winner in the Baroque Instrumental category. \n\nSince its inception, AVIE has had a relationship with the [[San Francisco Symphony]], coordinating international distribution and marketing of the orchestra\u2019s in-house label SFS Media which has won numerous Grammy Awards for its [[Symphonies of Mahler|Mahler Symphony cycle]] with conductor [[Michael Tilson Thomas]]. \n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.avie-records.com/}}\n\n{{UK-record-label-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Classical music record labels|Avie Records]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avie_Records"}
{"title_page": "Bad Boy for Life", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Bad Boys for Life}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Bad Boy for Life\n| cover      = BadBoyForLife.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Sean Combs|P. Diddy]], [[Black Rob]] and Mark Curry\n| album      = [[The Saga Continues...]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2001|07|10}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Minal |title=The Rhythm Section |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=DxUEAAAAMBAJ |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |work=Billboard |volume=113|issue=29|page=24|publisher=Google Books |date=July 21, 2001}}</ref>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|12\" vinyl]], [[Compact Disc single|CD single]], [[maxi single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=13}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]|[[Arista Records|Arista]]}}\n| writer     = Dorsey Wesley, Mark Curry, Robert Ross, Jamel Fisher, Drayton Goss\n| producer   = [[Megahertz (record producer)|Megahertz]]\n| chronology = [[Sean Combs|P. Diddy]]\n| prev_title = Let's Get It\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[Diddy (song)|Diddy]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Black Rob]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Whoa! (Black Rob song)|Whoa!]]\n | prev_year  = 2000\n | title      = Bad Boy for Life\n | year       = 2001\n | next_title = Let's Get it\n | next_year  = 2001\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Bad Boy for Life'''\" is a song by American rappers [[Sean Combs|P. Diddy]], [[Black Rob]] and Mark Curry, featured on Diddy's 2001 third album ''[[The Saga Continues...]]''. Produced by [[Megahertz (record producer)|Megahertz]] (Dorsey Wesley), it was released as the second [[Single (music)|single]] from the album in July 2001 and reached number 33 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/diddy-p214335/charts-awards/billboard-singles |title=Billboard Singles |work=Diddy Charts & Awards |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn reviews of the album, \"Bad Boy for Life\" has been identified as a declaration of strength by Diddy's label [[Bad Boy Records]]. Jason Birchmeier of music website [[Allmusic]] explains that the song summarises the claim \"that [the] Bad Boy empire is in fact still an empire\",<ref name=\"allmusic-2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-saga-continues-r538179/review |title=Review |work=Diddy - The Saga Continues |author=Jason Birchmeier |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref> while ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' reviewer David Browne similarly points out the lyric \"It's official/I survived what I been through\" as a declaration of strength.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,169233,00.html |title=The Saga Continues... Review |author=David Browne |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=July 30, 2001 |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref> Soren Baker of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' identifies \"Bad Boy for Life\", in addition to previous single \"Let's Get It\", as particularly important to the success of the album.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jul/22/entertainment/ca-25144 |title=P. Diddy & The Bad Boy Family, \"The Saga Continues ...\" |author=Soren Baker |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 22, 2001 |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for \"Bad Boy for Life\" was directed by [[Chris Robinson (director)|Chris Robinson]], filmed in June 2001 and released in early July, and features a number of cameo appearances including guitarist [[Dave Navarro]], drummer [[Travis Barker]], actor [[Ben Stiller]], actor [[Richard Dunn (actor)|Richard Dunn]], rappers [[Xzibit]], [[Ice Cube]], and [[Snoop Dogg]], boxer [[Mike Tyson]], television host [[Pat O'Brien (radio and television personality)|Pat O'Brien]], basketball players [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Baron Davis]] and rap rock band [[Crazy Town]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mvdbase.com/video.php?id=21261 |title=P. Diddy - \"Bad boy 4 life\" |publisher=mvdbase.com |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref> The video was nominated for Best Rap Video at both the 2002 MVPA Awards<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-music-video-production-association-announces-this-years-nominees-for-the-11th-annual-mvpa-awards-76781877.html |title=The Music Video Production Association Announces This Year's Nominees For the 11th Annual MVPA Awards |publisher=PRNewswire |date=April 4, 2002 |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref> and the [[2002 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2002/ |title=2002 Video Music Awards |work=MTV Video Music Awards |publisher=[[MTV]] |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==In other media==\nA song was used in 2015's \"Get Hard\" film by Etan Cohen. \nThe song was also used as part of an remix/mashup with ''[[Bad Boys (Inner Circle song)|Bad Boys]]'' by [[Inner Circle (band)|Inner Circle]] in the trailers for the 2020 film ''[[Bad Boys for Life]]'', the third installment in the [[Bad Boys (franchise)|''Bad Boys'' police action comedy franchise]] starring [[Will Smith]] and [[Martin Lawrence]].\n\nThe song was also heavily used by [[Tom Brady]] and the [[New England Patriots]] during their [[Super Bowl LIII]] run.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 12\" vinyl <small>(78612-79400-1)</small><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/P-Diddy-Black-Rob-Mark-Curry-Bad-Boy-For-Life/release/337553 |title=P. Diddy, Black Rob & Mark Curry - Bad Boy for Life (Vinyl) |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n| total_length    = 16:36\n\n| title1          = Bad Boy for Life\n| note1           = club mix\n| writer1         = Wesley, Curry, Ross, Fisher, Goss\n| length1         