 = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=13}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]|[[Arista Records|Arista]]}}\n| writer     = Dorsey Wesley, Mark Curry, Robert Ross, Jamel Fisher, Drayton Goss\n| producer   = [[Megahertz (record producer)|Megahertz]]\n| chronology = [[Sean Combs|P. Diddy]]\n| prev_title = Let's Get It\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[Diddy (song)|Diddy]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Black Rob]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Whoa! (Black Rob song)|Whoa!]]\n | prev_year  = 2000\n | title      = Bad Boy for Life\n | year       = 2001\n | next_title = Let's Get it\n | next_year  = 2001\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Bad Boy for Life'''\" is a song by American rappers [[Sean Combs|P. Diddy]], [[Black Rob]] and Mark Curry, featured on Diddy's 2001 third album ''[[The Saga Continues...]]''. Produced by [[Megahertz (record producer)|Megahertz]] (Dorsey Wesley), it was released as the second [[Single (music)|single]] from the album in July 2001 and reached number 33 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/diddy-p214335/charts-awards/billboard-singles |title=Billboard Singles |work=Diddy Charts & Awards |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn reviews of the album, \"Bad Boy for Life\" has been identified as a declaration of strength by Diddy's label [[Bad Boy Records]]. Jason Birchmeier of music website [[Allmusic]] explains that the song summarises the claim \"that [the] Bad Boy empire is in fact still an empire\",<ref name=\"allmusic-2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-saga-continues-r538179/review |title=Review |work=Diddy - The Saga Continues |author=Jason Birchmeier |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref> while ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' reviewer David Browne similarly points out the lyric \"It's official/I survived what I been through\" as a declaration of strength.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,169233,00.html |title=The Saga Continues... Review |author=David Browne |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=July 30, 2001 |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref> Soren Baker of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' identifies \"Bad Boy for Life\", in addition to previous single \"Let's Get It\", as particularly important to the success of the album.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jul/22/entertainment/ca-25144 |title=P. Diddy & The Bad Boy Family, \"The Saga Continues ...\" |author=Soren Baker |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 22, 2001 |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for \"Bad Boy for Life\" was directed by [[Chris Robinson (director)|Chris Robinson]], filmed in June 2001 and released in early July, and features a number of cameo appearances including guitarist [[Dave Navarro]], drummer [[Travis Barker]], actor [[Ben Stiller]], actor [[Richard Dunn (actor)|Richard Dunn]], rappers [[Xzibit]], [[Ice Cube]], and [[Snoop Dogg]], boxer [[Mike Tyson]], television host [[Pat O'Brien (radio and television personality)|Pat O'Brien]], basketball players [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Baron Davis]] and rap rock band [[Crazy Town]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mvdbase.com/video.php?id=21261 |title=P. Diddy - \"Bad boy 4 life\" |publisher=mvdbase.com |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref> The video was nominated for Best Rap Video at both the 2002 MVPA Awards<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-music-video-production-association-announces-this-years-nominees-for-the-11th-annual-mvpa-awards-76781877.html |title=The Music Video Production Association Announces This Year's Nominees For the 11th Annual MVPA Awards |publisher=PRNewswire |date=April 4, 2002 |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref> and the [[2002 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2002/ |title=2002 Video Music Awards |work=MTV Video Music Awards |publisher=[[MTV]] |accessdate=January 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==In other media==\nThe song was also used as part of an remix/mashup with ''[[Bad Boys (Inner Circle song)|Bad Boys]]'' by [[Inner Circle (band)|Inner Circle]] in the trailers for the 2020 film ''[[Bad Boys for Life]]'', the third installment in the [[Bad Boys (franchise)|''Bad Boys'' police action comedy franchise]] starring [[Will Smith]] and [[Martin Lawrence]].\n\nThe song was also heavily used by [[Tom Brady]] and the [[New England Patriots]] during their [[Super Bowl LIII]] run.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 12\" vinyl <small>(78612-79400-1)</small><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/P-Diddy-Black-Rob-Mark-Curry-Bad-Boy-For-Life/release/337553 |title=P. Diddy, Black Rob & Mark Curry - Bad Boy for Life (Vinyl) |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=January 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n| total_length    = 16:36\n\n| title1          = Bad Boy for Life\n| note1           = club mix\n| writer1         = Wesley, Curry, Ross, Fisher, Goss\n| length1         = 4:09\n\n| title2          = Bad Boy for Life\n| note2           = instrumental\n| writer2         = Wesley, Curry, Ross, Fisher, Goss\n| length2         = 4:09\n\n| title3          = Bad Boy for Life\n| note3           = radio mix\n| writer3         = Wesley, Curry, Ross, Fisher, Goss\n| length3         = 4:09\n\n| title4          = Bad Boy for Life\n| note4           = acapella\n| writer4         = Wesley, Curry, Ross, Fisher, Goss\n| length4         = 4:09\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = European CD single <small>([[Arista Records|Arista]] 74321 88431 2)</small><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/P-Diddy-Black-Rob-Mark-Curry-Bad-Boy-For-Life/release/1624161 |title=P. Diddy, Black Rob & Mark Curry - Bad Boy for Life (CD) |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=January 14, 201